    "summary": "B — Afterword, not Preface; would pre-interpret closing gesture",
    "content": "**B) The Translator's Afterword.**\n\nThis is exactly the kind of cross-traditional insight the Afterword was designed for. The five-point comparison is substantive scholarship that enriches the reader's understanding *after* they have encountered the passage themselves. Putting it in the Preface would pre-interpret the Appendix's closing gesture, which is one of the collection's most powerful moments -- the shift from technical philosophical apparatus back to the universality of everyday experience (\"当我们布置我们的办公桌、当面对夕阳按下快门...\"). The reader should arrive at \"我们正是这样的创造者，是自己生命和感受的诗人\" with their own accumulated experience of the collection behind them, not with a Heideggerian comparison already loaded.\n\nIn the Afterword, this finding belongs in Section B (Cross-Traditional Connections) under the existentialist positioning bullet, and it also connects naturally to Section C (The Experiential Method Revisited), because the shift from \"How do I become authentic?\" to \"How do I notice that I already am?\" is structurally identical to the collection's own method: the essays don't teach the reader something new so much as help the reader recognize what they are already doing. This self-referential dimension is best discussed after the reader has experienced it."
